Currently, most object detection frameworks operate at the instance level, providing class and location information via bounding boxes, while semantic segmentation delivers pixel-level predictions but typically requires costly dense annotations. Bridging this gap by integrating a weakly supervised segmentation head into a detection framework could unlock fine-grained understanding without sacrificing annotation efficiency.

One promising path forward is to design a unified architecture—perhaps based on DETR or a two-stage detector like Faster R-CNN—where the region proposals or query features are used not only for classification and box regression but also to drive a segmentation mask generator. The key innovation would be to train this mask generator in a weakly supervised manner: since we only have bounding box labels, we can use techniques like Class Activation Mapping (CAM), attention rollout, or uncertainty-guided pseudo-mask generation to produce initial segmentation targets. These pseudo-masks can then be refined through self-training or consistency regularization across augmentations (e.g., using Mean Teacher or EMA-based refinement).

A critical challenge will be dealing with the "box collapse" problem—where the model tends to activate only on the most discriminative parts within the box rather than the full damage extent. To counter this, we could integrate foreground expansion strategies such as erasing high-activation regions during training to encourage broader attention, or use shape priors learned from limited annotated masks in a meta-learning setup.

Moreover, we can explore dynamic label assignment: instead of treating all pixels within a box equally, the model could learn to weight pixel contributions based on activation certainty, effectively turning the bounding box into a soft supervision signal for segmentation. This would allow end-to-end training where the segmentation branch improves detection by providing richer feature gradients, creating a positive feedback loop.

The impact of such a framework would be substantial—imagine enabling precise crack localization in bridge inspections using only box-labeled datasets that already exist, thereby reducing labeling costs by orders of magnitude while enabling downstream tasks like severity grading or change tracking.

Would it make sense to ground this work in a specific application domain early on? For example, focusing on aerial damage assessment post-natural disasters could provide clear benchmarks and real-world validation opportunities.
