ion enhances segmentation (via tighter region proposals), forming a virtuous cycle.

New Idea: ```json
{
  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Co-evolving Detection and Weakly Supervised Segmentation via Attention-Guided Pseudo-Mask Refinement in Transformer Models for Pixel-Level Damage Localization with Bounding Box Supervision'. The central goal is to achieve high-fidelity pixel-level damage localization in industrial or infrastructure inspection scenarios using only bounding box annotations. Our approach introduces a dual-branch transformer architecture that jointly performs object detection and weakly supervised instance segmentation. The innovation lies in an iterative, attention-guided pseudo-mask refinement mechanism that leverages both self-attention and cross-attention maps from the vision transformer backbone to identify incomplete activations within annotated boxes. Specifically, during training, the model generates initial pseudo-masks using class activation maps, then applies an Attention-Guided Uncertainty Mining (AGUM) module to detect low-activation yet structurally plausible regions inside the bounding box—indicating potential missed damage areas. These regions are used to generate attention-conditioned augmentations (e.g., localized noise injection or cutout) to force the model to learn more comprehensive feature representations. A memory-augmented Pseudo-Mask Evolution (PME) buffer stores historical mask predictions across epochs, enabling temporal consistency modeling and voting-based refinement akin to ensemble learning. The refined pseudo-masks are then fed back into the segmentation branch as supervision, while also being used to modulate feature attention in the detection head via a Feature Alignment Loss, creating a co-evolutionary loop. Additionally, we incorporate a diffusion-like boundary regularization term inspired by denoising objectives, encouraging smooth and topologically sound mask boundaries. This framework significantly reduces reliance on manual pixel-wise labeling, making it highly applicable to real-world damage assess